ddle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Weston","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English:","habitational name from any of numerous places called Weston, from Old English <i>west</i> ‘west’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, settlement’.","topographic name from Middle English <i>atte west tun(e)</i> ‘at the west farmstead, settlement’ (Old English <i>west</i> + <i>tūn</i>), or from Middle English <i>(bi) weste(n)tune</i> (Old English <i>be westan tūne</i> or <i>be west in tūne</i>), denoting someone who lived either to the west of a settlement or in the western part of a settlement. The latter was a common surname in Sussex."],"variants":[{"name":"Wesson","meanings":["English (Midlands and Kent): variant of   Weston  .","History: John Wesson came from England to Salem, MA, in 1644."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Robert de Weston was born in 1113, in Weston under Lizard, Staffordshire, England, his father, Ralph de Weston, was 40 and his mother, Margaret de Leaver, was 35. He had at least 2 sons with Sibyl de Landa. He died after 1166, in Weston under Lizard, Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom, and was buried in Coverham, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"1113–Aft 1166":"1113–pärast 1166","1090–1180":"1090–1180","1113–1166":"1113–1166","1115–1141":"1115–1141","1136–1214":"1136–1214","1073–1126":"1073–1126","1078–1130":"1078–1130","1090":"1090","Aft 1166":"pärast 1166","1130":"1130","1141":"1141","1073":"1073","1180":"1180","1126":"1126","1104":"1104","1214":"1214","1115":"1115","1136":"1136","1113":"1113","1078":"1078","1166":"1166","after 1141":"pärast 1141","Weston under Lizard, Staffordshire, England":"Weston under Lizard, Staffordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Weston upon Trent, Staffordshire, England":"Weston, Staffordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England":"England","Coverham, Yorkshire, England":"Coverham, Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Middleham, Yorkshire, England":"Middleham, Yorkshire, England","Weston, Staffordshire, England":"Weston, Staffordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1113–Aft 1166":"1113–1166 jälkeen","1090–1180":"1090–1180","1113–1166":"1113–1166","1115–1141":"1115–1141","1136–1214":"1136–1214","1073–1126":"1073–1126","1078–1130":"1078–1130","1090":"1090","Aft 1166":"1166 jälkeen","1130":"1130","1141":"1141","1073":"1073","1180":"1180","1126":"1126","1104":"1104","1214":"1214","1115":"1115","1136":"1136","1113":"1113","1078":"1078","1166":"1166","after 1141":"1141 jälkeen","Weston under Lizard, Staffordshire, England":"Weston under Lizard, Staffordshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Weston upon Trent, Staffordshire, England":"Weston, Staffordshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","England":"England","Coverham, Yorkshire, England":"Coverham, Yorkshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Middleham, Yorkshire, England":"Middleham, Yorkshire, England","Weston, Stafford